---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Contact | latepaycalc.com';
const description = 'Contact latepaycalc.com with corrections, formula questions, guide feedback, or technical issues.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Contact</h1>
  <p>Email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We review every message and respond to substantive corrections and feedback within five business days.</p>

  <h2>What we respond to</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Formula corrections and statute citations.</strong> If we've cited a wrong statute section, used an outdated penalty amount, or applied a formula incorrectly, we want to know. Include the page URL, the specific claim you believe is wrong, and the correct authority if you have it. Statutory corrections are our highest priority.</li>
    <li><strong>Errors or unclear language in guides.</strong> If a guide's explanation is confusing, contradicts the cited statute, or is missing important nuance — especially for fast-moving areas like state-level wage law — please flag it with page and section.</li>
    <li><strong>Suggestions for new content.</strong> We prioritize new guides and calculator features based on what users actually need. If there's a late-payment scenario we haven't covered — a specific state's penalty structure, a B2B edge case, an industry-specific rule — let us know.</li>
    <li><strong>Technical issues.</strong> If the calculator isn't loading, producing obviously wrong results, or has a display problem on your device, describe what you're seeing and include your browser and device type if possible.</li>
    <li><strong>Press and partnership inquiries.</strong> If you're writing about late-payment law and need background or a quote, reach out. We don't do paid placements, but we're happy to talk to journalists covering wage theft, commercial credit, or related topics.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What we don't respond to</h2>
  <p>We can't evaluate your specific dispute, advise you on whether your late-fee clause is enforceable, or recommend attorneys. For your situation, contact a licensed attorney in your state. For employment wage claims, your state labor agency offers a free filing process that doesn't require a lawyer — see our <a href="/guides/what-to-do-if-paid-late">what to do if you're paid late</a> guide for step-by-step guidance.</p>
</BaseLayout>
